bib.title: Polarization and angular distribution of the neutronsfrom 14C(p,n) reaction and the tensor force

free_txt: OG
The proton beam energy spread due to energy loss in
the gas targets varied between +-0.18 MeV at Ep = 7.2
MeV and +-0.14 MeV at Ep = 13.3 MeV.
The neutron detector was a 5x5-cm stilbene
scintillator located 30 cm from the helium scatterer.
The method consists of precessing the neutron
magnetic moment plus and minus 90 degrees with a
suitably designed solenoid to obtain the equivalent
"left" and "right" scattering measurements.
The analyzer was liquid helium, and the angle
of scattering from the helium was 60 degrees.
The cell filled with CO2 gas to a pressure of 1.5 atm.
For the lower-energy measurements, Ep = 7.2, 8.8, and
10.4 MeV, the gas target is 2.5x2.5-cm gas cell lined
with Ta. The entrance window was 0.0013-cm Ta and was
supported by a gold grid whose transmission was
approximately 90%. The cell was filled with 14CO2 gas
to a pressure of 1.5 atm.
For the measurements at Ep = 10.4, 11.7, 12.6, and
13.3 MeV, a 2.5x2.5-cm target with nickel entrance and
windows (9-mg/cm2 unsupported Ni windows) was used. The
beam stopper was also nickel and was located some 30 cm
from the gas cell. The cell was filled with 14CO2 gas
to a pressure of two atm.

The error on polarization was computed from
the statistical counting error on the product P(He)*P,
where P(He) is the polarization of the neutrons
scattered from the helium and P is the polarization of
the neutrons from the (p,n) reaction, since the
statistical counting errors are much larger than the
uncertainties in the values of P(He).
